---
id: weegloo-web-hosting-rules
type: rule
title: Weegloo WebHosting Rules
description: >
  These rules apply specifically to WebHosting deployment and update operations.
  They define mandatory build, packaging, and update constraints for hosting web projects via MCP.
---

rules:
  - section: Build Output Requirements
    items:
      - The web project must be built using `index.html` as the entry point.
      - The `env.js` file must remain as a separate file and must not be bundled, transformed, or compressed.

  - section: Runtime env.js (LLM checklist)
    items:
      - Path on the hosted site must be **`./env.js`** (same directory as `index.html` in the ZIP / export root). The HTML must load it with a **synchronous** script early in `<head>` (e.g. `<script src="./env.js"></script>`) **before** application bundles so `window.__ENV__` exists when the app runs.
      - Required JavaScript shape (plain script, no modules): **`window.__ENV__ = { "KEY": "value", ... };`** Use **string** values. For Next.js public client env, keys should match **`NEXT_PUBLIC_*`** names (e.g. `NEXT_PUBLIC_WEEGLOO_DELIVERY_ACCESS_TOKEN`).
      - Do not import `env.js` from webpack/Turbopack; keep it as a **static asset** copied to export root. Changing values must **not** require a rebuild.
      - **Next.js App Router:** the framework may inject many `<script>` tags before layout children. If `window.__ENV__` is undefined at runtime, use a **post-build step** to insert `<script src="./env.js"></script>` **immediately after** the opening `<head>` tag in exported HTML (this project does that in `scripts/stage-careerresume-out.mjs`).
      - **`.env.local`** (or CI env) is for **local development / build-time fallbacks** only; **hosted runtime** configuration is **`env.js`** so operators can edit values on the server or via WebHosting env update MCP without redeploying the full site when only env changes.

  - section: Packaging Requirements
    items:
      - The build output must be compressed into a ZIP archive before upload.
      - The `index.html` file must be located at the root level of the ZIP archive.
      - All built assets (JS, CSS, images, fonts, videos, etc.) must be included in the ZIP archive alongside `index.html`.
      - Nested directory structures that place `index.html` below the root are not allowed.

  - section: Deployment Process (MCP Only)
    items:
      - **Deployment MUST use Weegloo MCP tools only.** Do NOT use deploy scripts (e.g. `scripts/deploy-weegloo.mjs`), direct `fetch`/API calls, or any method other than MCP.
      - An `Upload` resource must be created using the `CreateUpload` MCP tool (user-weegloo-upload) with the generated ZIP file.
      - A `WebHosting` resource must be created or updated using the `cma_CreateWebHosting` or `cma_UpdateOneWebHosting` MCP tool (user-weegloo) based on the previously created `Upload` resource.
      - Direct API calls, manual uploads, or deploy scripts outside MCP tools are strictly prohibited.

  - section: Subdomain (User Input Required)
    items:
      - The `subdomain` MUST be obtained from the user. Never assume, infer, or default it (e.g. do not use project name, package name, or any derived value).
      - If the user has not explicitly provided a subdomain, STOP the deployment workflow and ask the user to provide one.
      - Do not proceed with build, upload, or WebHosting creation until the user has provided a subdomain.

  - section: Create WebHosting
    items:
      - A `subdomain` value must be provided when creating a `WebHosting` resource.
      - The subdomain must come from explicit user input; see "Subdomain (User Input Required)" section.
      - The provided subdomain must be globally unique within the service.
      - Before creating the resource, the `CheckSubdomain` MCP tool must be used to verify that the subdomain is not already in use.
      - The uniqueness check must be performed prior to attempting resource creation.
      - If the `CheckSubdomain` tool indicates that the subdomain already exists, the creation request must be rejected.
      - Bypassing the `CheckSubdomain` tool or skipping the uniqueness validation is not allowed.

  - section: Redeployment (Updating Existing WebHosting)
    items:
      - To redeploy an updated build to an existing subdomain, follow this sequence. 1) Build and ZIP the new output. 2) Create a new `Upload` resource. 3) Retrieve the existing `WebHosting` resource using `GetOneWebHosting` to obtain the current `sys.version`. 4) Call `UpdateOneWebHosting` with the new `Upload` reference and the current `sys.version` in the `X-Weegloo-Version` header.
      - "`UpdateOneWebHosting` is a full replacement (PUT). All required fields (`name`, `upload`, etc.) must be included in the request, not just the changed fields."
      - There is no need to delete and recreate the `WebHosting` resource. Use the update tool instead.

  - section: Update Rules (env.js Only)
    items:
      - If only the `env.js` file is changed, the website must not be fully redeployed.
      - In the case of an `env.js`-only change, update the existing `WebHosting` resource using the MCP tool.
      - When updating environment values, the `env.js` file may be parsed into key-value pairs and applied as `environments` in the `WebHosting` resource.
      - When parsing `env.js` for MCP, expect the pattern **`window.__ENV__ = { ... };`** (object literal with string keys/values). Strip comments if present before parsing.

  - section: Validation Requirements
    items:
      - Before upload or update, it must be verified that `index.html` exists at the root of the build output.
      - After deployment, verify the `WebHosting` resource state is `COMPLETED` by polling the `GetOneWebHosting` MCP tool.